ORDER

On January 28, 2008, this Court issued
  an opinion affirming the circuit judgeâ€™s award of statutory attorneysâ€™ fees for
  counsel who successfully litigated the claims of a class of TERI participants
  (Respondents/Appellants in the instant action) against the State and the South
  Carolina Retirement System.[1]Â  Layman v. The State
    of South Carolina and The South Carolina Retirement System, Op. No. 26427 (S.C. Sup. Ct. filed January 28, 2008) (Shearouse Adv. Sh. No. 4 at 50) [hereinafter Layman II].Â 
  Beginning with a lodestar calculation based on the timesheets in the record
  before this Court and on counselâ€™s hourly rates, this Court enhanced the lodestar
  figure with a multiplier to reflect the exceptional circumstances of the case, and
  modified the circuit judgeâ€™s calculation of attorneysâ€™ fees to award counsel
  for the TERI plaintiffs $445,226.60.Â  Id. at 73. 
Counsel for the TERI plaintiffs filed a petition
  for rehearing, and in their return, the State and the Retirement System moved
  for leave to supplement the record.Â  We deny the motions of both parties and
  issue this order modifying the award of attorneysâ€™ fees to reflect the
  additional fees and costs incurred by counsel for the TERI plaintiffs in
  litigating the issue of attorneysâ€™ fees.Â  In doing so, we note that counsel for
  the TERI plaintiffs did not set forth these additional fees and costs in the
  record before this Court in Layman II even though counsel were
  presumably aware that the Stateâ€™s and the Retirement Systemâ€™s theory of the
  case was that under the relevant statute, attorneysâ€™ fees were to be awarded
  based solely on counselâ€™s hourly rate and time expended.Â  While the matter
  could be remanded at this juncture for a calculation of attorneysâ€™ fees in
  accordance with the methodology outlined in Layman II, in the interest
  of fairness and in ending this litigation without further accrual of fees by
  either side, we modify our original award of attorneysâ€™ fees to include this
  additional time expended by counsel.
